      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong>Ans. C)</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Beta-hydroxybutyrate.</strong> </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Ketone bodies</strong> include <strong>acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate and acetone,</strong> which are produced by the <strong>liver in the fasting</strong> state by<strong> beta-oxidation of fatty acids.</strong>&nbsp; </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Then these <strong>ketone bodies </strong>are released <strong>into</strong> the<strong> bloodstream</strong> &rarr;used as <strong>alternative energy</strong> sources for<strong> muscle, kidney,</strong> <strong>and brain</strong>.&nbsp; </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">But the<strong> brain</strong> specifically requires a <strong>small amount of circulating glucose</strong> to function and the<strong> amount required</strong> is <strong>reduced</strong> when<strong> ketone body </strong>sources are available.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: Coenzyme A:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> It is found in <strong>mitochondria</strong> and<strong> carries acetyl groups</strong> into the <strong>TCA cycle.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: Beta-carotene:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> It is a<strong> vitamin </strong>with <strong>antioxidant properties.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: Apoprotein:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> It is<strong> one</strong> of the <strong>proteins</strong> that<strong> hold lipoproteins together.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">During <strong>prolonged fasting</strong>, the <strong>body shifts to ketosis</strong>, a <strong>metabolic state</strong> where it uses<strong> ketone bodies</strong> as an <strong>alternative energy source.</strong> <strong>Beta-hydroxybutyrate</strong> is one of the <strong>primary ketone bodies</strong> produced by the <strong>liver from fatty acids</strong> in the <strong>absence </strong>of sufficient <strong>glucose.</strong> The <strong>brain can utilize beta-hydroxybutyrate</strong> efficiently in place of <strong>glucose,</strong> allowing for <strong>sustained</strong> <strong>cognitive function</strong> and <strong>energy levels</strong> despite <strong>low blood glucose.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e: p 148-149.</span></strong></span></span></p>",
