      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Free fatty acid breakdown &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\">&nbsp;<strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>presenting features </strong>are suggestive of <strong>type 1 diabetes.&nbsp; </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The primary source of<strong> ketones is free fatty acid breakdown.&nbsp; </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Ketone body formation </strong>occurs as follows:<strong> Insulin deficiency</strong> &rarr; <strong>activated lipolysis</strong> &rarr; <strong>increased plasma free fatty acids</strong>&nbsp; &rarr; <strong>increased hepatic fatty acids</strong> &rarr; accelerated<strong> ketogenesis </strong>&rarr; <strong>ketosis</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri, sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><u>other options:</u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Gluconeogenesis:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> While <strong>gluconeogenesis</strong> involves the production of <strong>glucose</strong> from <strong>non-carbohydrate sources,</strong> it<strong> does not</strong> directly lead to<strong> ketone production.</strong> It is a<strong> glucose-</strong>generating process that occurs in the<strong> liver and kidneys.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. Glycogenolysis:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> This process involves the <strong>breakdown of glycogen stored </strong>in the <strong>liver</strong> and<strong> muscle</strong> into <strong>glucose. </strong>Glycogenolysis<strong> does not</strong> directly result in <strong>ketone production</strong>; instead, it provides an <strong>immediate source of glucose.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D. Triglyceride breakdown:</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"> Triglyceride breakdown in <strong>adipose tissue </strong>leads to the release of<strong> glycerol and free fatty acids</strong>. While the<strong> breakdown of triglycerides </strong>initiates the <strong>release of fatty acids</strong>, it is the<strong> subsequent &beta;-oxidation</strong> of these<strong> fatty acids</strong> in the <strong>liver </strong>that leads <strong>directly to ketone production</strong>. Therefore, <strong>&quot;free fatty acid breakdown&quot;</strong> is a<strong> more specific</strong> answer in the context of<strong> ketone production.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Ketone bodies</strong> are produced primarily in the<strong> live</strong>r through the process of <strong>ketogenesis,</strong> which occurs when there is an<strong> increased breakdown of free fatty acids</strong>. This situation typically arises in states of<strong> decreased carbohydrate </strong>availability or<strong> impaired glucose utilization,</strong> leading the <strong>body to switch to fat </strong>as an <strong>alternative energy source</strong>. In this patient&#39;s case, the <strong>presence</strong> of <strong>ketones in the urine</strong> suggests that her<strong> body is utilizing fatty acids for energy,</strong> which results in the production of <strong>ketones </strong>as a <strong>byproduct of fatty acid metabolism in the liver.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/e: p 231-233</span></strong></span></span></p>",
