      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. A) Diabetic ketoacidosis&nbsp;</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">This patient presents with classic signs and symptoms of diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA): altered mental status, dehydration, hypotension, metabolic acidosis, and the characteristic fruity odor of acetone on her breath.&nbsp;</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Treatment:&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The patient Should be rehydrated with normal saline given intravenously (IV) and insulin IV.&nbsp;</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Blood glucose, ketone bodies and electrolytes should be measured periodically.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation</u></strong>:</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Uncontrolled diabetes</strong>: While the patient does have diabetes, the specific presentation with acidosis, ketonemia, and the clinical context suggest DKA rather than just uncontrolled diabetes.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Lactic acidosis</strong>: Lactic acidosis presents with acidosis but is typically associated with severe hypoperfusion or hypoxia, and the ketone levels would not be elevated as they are in this case.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D. Diabetes insipidus</strong>: Diabetes insipidus is characterized by polyuria and polydipsia due to a deficiency of antidiuretic hormone (ADH) or kidney's response to ADH, but it does not cause hyperglycemia, acidosis, or ketonemia.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Diabetic ketoacidosis is an acute, potentially life-threatening complication of diabetes characterized by hyperglycemia, ketosis, and metabolic acidosis. Clinical presentation typically includes dehydration, Kussmaul breathing, fruity breath odor (acetone), altered mental status, and hypotension.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ref</strong>: Harper 30/e: p 231.</span></p>",
