      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. D) All the above</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Normally the <strong>rate of synthesis </strong>of <strong>ketone bodies </strong>by the <strong>liver </strong>is <strong>well </strong>balanced by their metabolism by <strong>extrahepatic tissues </strong>&rarr; causes <strong>blood level of ketone bodies </strong>&lt;&lt; <strong>1 mg/dL </strong>and only <strong>traces </strong>are <strong>excreted in urine</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/04/11/10.jpg\" style=\"height:472px; width:602px\" /></span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">When the <strong>rate of synthesis </strong>exceeds the <strong>ability of utilization </strong>&rarr;&nbsp;accumulation of <strong>ketone bodies in blood </strong>(<strong>Ketonemia</strong>), <strong>excretion </strong>in <strong>urine </strong>(<strong>ketonuria</strong>) and smell of <strong>acetone </strong>in <strong>breath. </strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>All these three </strong>constitute together to form <strong>ketosis</strong>.</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: Ketonemia</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: This term refers to the<strong> presence of ketone bodies </strong>in the <strong>blood</strong>. It is one of the <strong>hallmark signs of ketosis</strong>, indicating that the body is <strong>using ketones </strong>as an <strong>alternative energy </strong>source due to <strong>low glucose availability or utilization.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: Ketonuria</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Ketonuria denotes the <strong>excretion </strong>of <strong>ketone bodies </strong>in the <strong>urine</strong>. It&#39;s a <strong>direct </strong>result of <strong>ketonemia; </strong>when <strong>ketone </strong>levels in the <strong>blood rise</strong>, the <strong>kidneys filter </strong>some of these <strong>ketones out</strong>, which then <strong>appear </strong>in the <strong>urine</strong>. It&#39;s often used as a <strong>diagnostic indicator for ketosis.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C: Smell of acetone</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: <strong>Acetone, </strong>one of the <strong>three </strong>primary <strong>ketone bodies </strong>(alongside <strong>acetoacetate and beta-hydroxybutyrate</strong>), can be <strong>exhaled </strong>in the <strong>breath </strong>when in <strong>ketosis</strong>, leading to a <strong>distinct fruity or nail polish </strong>remover-like <strong>smell</strong>. This is a common <strong>anecdotal </strong>marker of being in a<strong> state of ketosis,</strong> especially <strong>noted</strong> among<strong> individuals</strong> following a <strong>ketogenic diet.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Ketosis </strong>is characterized by <strong>elevated levels of ketone bodies</strong>, which can manifest as <strong>ketonemia </strong>(presence of ketones in the blood), <strong>ketonuria </strong>(presence of ketones in the urine), and a <strong>distinctive acetone smell </strong>in the breath. Understanding these manifestations provides insights into the <strong>body&#39;s metabolic state </strong>during <strong>carbohydrate restriction</strong>, <strong>fasting, or uncontrolled diabetes</strong>, highlighting the <strong>body&#39;s adaptive mechanisms </strong>to <strong>alternative energy sources</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"PT-BR\" style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: DM Vasudevan 9/e: p 213</span></strong></span></span></p>",
