      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. C)&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">RBCs</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Red blood cells (RBCs) </strong>are <strong>unable </strong>to utilize <strong>ketone bodies </strong>due to the <strong>absence of mitochondria</strong>, where <strong>ketone bodies </strong>are converted into <strong>acetyl-CoA </strong>and then enter the <strong>citric acid cycle </strong>for <strong>energy production</strong>. <strong>RBCs </strong>rely solely on <strong>glycolysis </strong>for their <strong>energy needs</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Other Options:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A: Brain</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: The brain can u<strong>tilize ketone bodies </strong>as an <strong>alternative energy source </strong>during prolonged <strong>fasting </strong>or <strong>carbohydrate restriction</strong>, after an <strong>adaptation period</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option B: Skeletal muscle</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Skeletal muscles can use <strong>ketone bodies </strong>for <strong>energy</strong>, especially during <strong>prolonged periods of fasting </strong>or <strong>intense exercise </strong>when <strong>glucose </strong>availability is <strong>limited</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D: Cardiac muscle</span></strong><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: The heart can <strong>efficiently </strong>use <strong>ketone bodies </strong>as a <strong>fuel source</strong>, particularly in conditions where <strong>fatty acid oxidation </strong>is <strong>compromised </strong>or in the context of <strong>increased energy demand.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The<strong> ketone bodies </strong>are formed in the <strong>liver by mitochondrial enzyme thiolase </strong>and are utilized by <strong>extrahepatic tissues</strong> such as <strong>heart muscle</strong>, <strong>renal cortex, skeletal muscle,</strong> and <strong>brain</strong>, which prefer the<strong> ketone bodies </strong>as <strong>alternate sources </strong>of <strong>energy</strong>, if <strong>glucose </strong>is <strong>not </strong>available.</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong>Ketone bodies </strong>are <strong>not </strong>utilised by<strong> RBCs </strong>due to the <strong>absence of mitochondria</strong></span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref</span></span></u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">: Harper 30/ed ,pg 227 </span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> </span></strong></span></span></p>",
